                <td>1</td>
              <td><strong>Dalton's</strong> Atom (1805)</td>
                <td>First to develop the principles of atomic theory.</td>
                <td>No concept of the internal atomic structure (electron and nuclei).
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>2</td>
              <td><strong>Thomson</strong> Plum Pudding Atom (1904)</td>
                <td>First to go beyond the atom and discover the first subatomic particle, the electron.</td>
              <td>No concept of the nuclei.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>3</td>
                <td><strong>Rutherford</strong> Nuclear Atom (1910)</td>
                <td>First to discover the atom contains a positively charged nucleus in the center.</td>
              <td>No concept of quantized energy.
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>4</td>
                <td>Quantized <strong>Bohr</strong> Atom (1913)</td>
                <td>First to discover electron's orbit the nuclei with quantized energy.</td>
              <td>No concept of electron's wave-like behavior and that electron shells can be more than a sphere.
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>5</td>
              <td><strong>Quantum</strong> Atom (1920+)</td>
              <td>First to incorporate the electron's wave-like behavior in defining the orbitals. 
                The atomic orbitals wave function provides the probability of finding the electron's position, rather than a defined 'path' the electron takes.
               
